   INTRODUCTION

    GuidePrefs is a Workbench preferences editor for the AmigaGuide«
   document system. AmigaGuide« reads its settings from some environment
   variables in the ENV:AmigaGuide directory. These vars are easy the set
   by hand, if you are familiar with AmigaDOS and the Shell, but I think that
   this little program is even more easier to use. The GuidePrefs editor
   belongs in the Workbench Prefs drawer. Simply drag the GuidePrefs icon
   to this drawer and the installation is completed.
   
    note: if you are not familiar with the AmigaGuide« system, or you're not
          using it, then there is no reason why you should use GuidePrefs.
          It is simply useless if you never read AmigaGuide« databases.
          However, if you are reading this doc through AmigaGuide«, you
          already are an AmigaGuide« user.
         
    The GuidePrefs editor is a much similar editor like the standard
   editors in the Workbench Prefs drawer. I tried to implement all the
   features of the standard editors to make it fit real good in the system.
   
    The settings of the GuidePrefs editor are stored in the
   ENVARC:AmigaGuide directory permanently. At bootup-time, they are copied
   in the ENV:AmigaGuide directory, from which AmigaGuide« and GuidePrefs
   read them. YOU HAVE TO MAKE SURE THAT THE AMIGAGUIDE DIRECTORY EXISTS. IF
   NOT, YOU SHOULD CREATE IT IN THE ENVARC: DIRECTORY AND REBOOT YOUR AMIGA!
@ENDNODE
       

@NODE Menus "GuidePrefs menus"
@TOC Main

    GuidePrefss' menus provide a good overview and quick access to the
   build in functions. Here follows a description of all the menus
   and their meaning:

   @{" Project " LINK MN_Project} basic program functions.

   @{" Edit " LINK MN_Edit} edit settings.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MN_Project "GuidePrefs Project menu"

    The Project menu groups all the basic operations you can do with
   GuidePrefs.

     @{" About...  " LINK IT_About}

     @{" Quit...   " LINK IT_Quit}
@ENDNODE

@NODE MN_Edit "GuidePrefs Edit menu"

    The Edit menu groups somee editing functions of the settings.

     @{" Reset To Defaults " LINK IT_Defaults}
     @{" Last Saved        " LINK IT_LastSaved}
     @{" Restore           " LINK IT_Restore}
@ENDNODE

@NODE IT_About "GuidePrefs About menu-item"

    This item opens the About window. Program control returns after you have
   closed this window.

    In this little window, you can see the version of the GuidePrefs
   program that you are using. There is also an indication of the author
   who made the locale-catalog of your language.

   Shortcut: Right Amiga + ?
@ENDNODE

@NODE IT_Quit "GuidePrefs Quit menu-item"

    This item is selected to quit the GuidePrefs program. The editor quits
   without asking a confirmation from the user. Unsaved settings will be
   lost.

   Shortcut: Right Amiga + Q
@ENDNODE

@NODE IT_Defaults "GuidePrefs Reset To Defaults menu-item"

    This item is selected to reset all settings to their default values.
   There are no default AmigaGuide paths, so the list is empty.

   Shortcut: Right Amiga + D
@ENDNODE

@NODE IT_LastSaved "GuidePrefs Last Saved menu-item"

    This item is selected to read all settings stored in the
   ENVARC:AmigaGuide directory.

   Shortcut: Right Amiga + L
@ENDNODE

@NODE IT_Restore "GuidePrefs Restore menu-item"

    This item is selected to undo the last change that was made. Currently,
   this has no effect on changes to the AmigaGuide paths because I didn't
   found an elegant way tot keep track of list-changes (yet!),

   Shortcut: Right Amiga + R
@ENDNODE

@NODE AGPWindow "GuidePrefs Window"

    The GuidePrefs editor window is build of 10 gadgets. Every gadget has
   a specific function.


   +------------------------------+
   |                              |   @{" Link Rendering " LINK GD_Link}
   |                              |                      O
   |     @{" AmigaGuide Paths  " LINK GD_Paths}      |                      O
   |                              |                      O
   +------------------------------+                      O
   @{" Add... " LINK GD_Add} @{" Delete " LINK GD_Delete}+-------------+

   +-------------------------+ +-------------------------+
   |                         | |                         |
   |                         | |                         |
   |   @{" AmigaGuide Pens  " LINK GD_Pens}    | |      @{" Pen Colour  " LINK GD_Colour}      |
   |                         | |                         |
   +-------------------------+ |                         |
   +-------------------------+ +-------------------------+

   @{" Save " LINK GD_Save}                  @{" Use " LINK GD_Use}                  @{" Cancel " LINK GD_Cancel}
@ENDNODE

@NODE GD_Paths "GuidePrefs AmigaGuide Paths gadget"

    This gadget is used to specify the search paths for the AmigaGuide«
   System. The AmigaGuide« document reader scans these paths when a certain
   link in a database is connected with a node in another database or file.
   If the link does not specify a path (e.g. INCLUDE:dos/dos.h), then the
   paths in this listview-gadget are used as default paths.

    You can add paths with the @{" Add... " LINK GD_Add} gadget and remove paths with
   the @{" Delete " LINK GD_Delete} gadget. In addition, you can edit paths by hand with
   the string gadget next to the Delete gadget.  When you select a path,
   it appears in the string gadget and then you can edit the path by
   clicking inside the string gadget box. 
@ENDNODE

@NODE GD_Link "GuidePrefs Link Rendering gadget"

    This gadget lets you choose the type of link rendering in AmigaGuide«
   documents. Links are the mouse-sensitive words or phrases which connect
   items with another database document, an ARexx/AmigaDOS command or a
   simple text file.

    There are four types of link rendering:

   BUTTON: the default setting, draws an embossed box arround the link.

   UNDERLINE: underlines the link.

   BOLD: prints the link in boldface text.

   ITALIC: prints the link in italic text.
@ENDNODE

@NODE GD_Add "GuidePrefs Add gadget"

    Clicking this gadget pops up a standard directory requester which
   allows you to select a valid AmigaDOS path from your filesystem.

    When you selected the right path, all you have to do is clicking on
   the OK gadget to add the path to the list.
@ENDNODE

@NODE GD_Delete "GuidePrefs Delete gadget"

    Clicking this gadget will remove the currently selected path from the
   list.

    WARNING: because there is no confirmation requester and the Restore
             menu item does not restore path-changes (yet), there is no
             other way to recover removed paths but to re-select them with
             the @{" Add... " LINK GD_Add} gadget.
@ENDNODE

@NODE GD_Pens "GuidePrefs AmigaGuide Pens gadget"

    This listview gadget lets you select one of the pens used to render
   AmigaGuide® documents. When you select a pen, you can change it's colour
   with the @{" Pen Colour  " LINK GD_Colour} gadget.
@ENDNODE

@NODE GD_Colour "GuidePrefs Pen Colour gadget"
  
    This gadget displays the pen colour of the pen you selected with the
   @{" AmigaGuide Pens  " LINK GD_Pens} gadget. By clicking on other colours on the
   palette gadget, you can change the colour from the pen.
@ENDNODE

@NODE GD_Save "GuidePrefs Save gadget"

    This gadget is selected to save the settings permanently in the
   ENVARC:AmigaGuide directory.
@ENDNODE

@NODE GD_Use "GuidePrefs Use gadget"

    This gadget is selected to use the settings until the computer is
   rebooted. Settings are saved in ENV:AmigaGuide directory.
@ENDNODE

@NODE GD_Cancel "GuidePrefs Cancel gadget"

    This gadget is selected to cancel all changes and leave the editor
   without saving anything.
@ENDNODE

